Q: Why are Volumes needed in Unity Catalog?
Volumes in Unity Catalog are used to manage and govern non-tabular data (files) within Databricks, while tables are used for structured data.

Problem Before Volumes

Before Unity Catalog Volumes, organizations stored files directly in ADLS Gen2, S3, or Blob Storage and accessed them using storage credentials or mount points. This created challenges:

      Limited governance on files
      Access control managed separately from Databricks
      Difficult auditing and lineage tracking
      Security risks from shared storage keys
      Why Volumes Were Introduced

Volumes provide a governed storage layer for files under Unity Catalog.

They allow you to store and manage:

CSV files
JSON files
Images
PDFs
ML models
Configuration files
Checkpoint files
Any unstructured or semi-structured data
Benefits of Volumes

1. Centralized Governance

Permissions are controlled through Unity Catalog.
    GRANT READ FILES ON VOLUME sales_catalog.raw.sales_volume TO analyst_gr

2. Auditability
All file access activities are tracked through Unity Catalog audit logs.

Example:
      Who uploaded a file?
      Who modified a file?
      When was it accessed?

3. Fine-Grained Security 
You can grant:
        READ FILES
        WRITE FILES
to specific users or groups.

4.Better Alternative to DBFS Mounts

Databricks recommends using Volumes instead of DBFS mounts because mounts are legacy and not governed by Unity Catalog.

Types of Volumes
  Managed Volume  -- Databricks manages the underlying storage location.
              CREATE VOLUME customer_docs

External Volume   --Points to an existing ADLS Gen2 container/folder.
        
CREATE EXTERNAL VOLUME sales_files
LOCATION 'abfss://raw@storageaccount.dfs.core.windows.net/sales/';
===============================================================================================

Scenario

Your company receives daily CSV files from external vendors into an ADLS Gen2 container.

Without Unity Catalog, you might:

Give users direct access to the storage account.
Share Service Principal credentials or SAS tokens.
Manage permissions at the storage layer.

This creates:

Security risks
Credential management overhead
Limited auditing
Poor governance
Solution Using Unity Catalog Volume
Step 1: Create a Storage Credential

Use a Managed Identity or Service Principal to access ADLS.

Step 2: Create an External Location

        CREATE EXTERNAL LOCATION vendor_ext_loc
        URL 'abfss://vendor@companystorage.dfs.core.windows.net/'
        WITH STORAGE CREDENTIAL vendor_cred

Step 3: Create an External Volume

    CREATE EXTERNAL VOLUME vendor_csv_volume
    LOCATION 'abfss://vendor@companystorage.dfs.core.windows.net/dailyfiles/'

Step 4: Grant Permissions

        GRANT READ FILES
        ON VOLUME vendor_csv_volume
        TO data_analyst_team

Step 5: Access Files

          df = spark.read.csv(
              "/Volumes/main/raw/vendor_csv_volume/customers.csv",
              header=True
          )

